          From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia                            Jump to:     navigation,      search           Ryszard Tarasiewicz     Personal information   Full name Ryszard Jerzy Tarasiewicz   Date of birth (1962-04-27) 27 April 1962 (age 54)   Place of birth Wrocław, Poland   Height 1.77 m (5 ft 9 1⁄2 in)   Playing position Midfielder   Club information    Current team  ? (manager)   Senior career*   Years Team Apps† (Gls)†   1979–1989 Śląsk Wrocław 214 (56)   1989–1990 Neuchâtel Xamax FC 30 (11)   1990–1992 AS Nancy 54 (15)   1992–1994 RC Lens 0 (0)   1994–1995 Besançon RC 22 (2)   1995–1996 Etoile Carouge     National team   1984–1991 Poland 58 (9)   Teams managed   2004–2006 Śląsk Wrocław   2006–2007 Jagiellonia Białystok   2007–2010 Śląsk Wrocław   2011–2012 ŁKS Łódź   2012 Pogoń Szczecin   2013–2014 Zawisza Bydgoszcz   2014–2015 Korona Kielce    * Senior club appearances and goals counted for the domestic league only. † Appearances (goals)   Ryszard Jerzy Tarasiewicz (born 27 April 1962 in Wrocław) is a Polish retired football player and current manager.    Contents   1 Honours  1.1 Club   2 Career  2.1 Club 2.2 National team   3 Managerial career 4 References 5 External links    Honours[edit] Club[edit]   Śląsk Wrocław   Polish Cup: 1986-87    Zawisza Bydgoszcz   Polish Cup: 2013–14 I Liga: 2012–13  Career[edit] Club[edit] After playing 10 years for Śląsk Wrocław, he left Poland in 1989 and played for Neuchâtel Xamax (Switzerland) and AS Nancy, RC Lens, Besançon RC (all in France). National team[edit] He played for the Polish national team (58 matches/9 goals)[1] and was a participant of the 1986 FIFA World Cup. Managerial career[edit] Just like his active career, Tarasiewicz started his managing career at Śląsk Wrocław. After 2 years, where he led the club to the II liga, he resigned due to conflicts with the club's then president Edward Ptak. He went on to coach Jagiellonia Białystok, but was sacked before the end of the season due to poor results. On 19 June 2007 he yet again signed a contract with Śląsk Wrocław. In 2008, he led the club back to the highest Polish football league, the Ekstraklasa, making him the first manager in the club's history, who promoted twice with his team. On 22 September 2010 he was sacked from his position due to a poor start to the 2010-11 Ekstraklasa season. On 7 November 2011 he signed a contract with ŁKS Łódź.[2] References[edit]   ^ http://www.kadra.pl/index.php?strona=historia&dzial=reprezentanci&litera=S ^ http://www.lkslodz.pl/pilka,klub,news,802   External links[edit]  Profile at 90minut.pl Profile at weltfussball.de          v t e   Poland squad – 1986 FIFA World Cup          1 Młynarczyk 2 Przybyś 3 Żmuda 4 Ostrowski 5 Wójcicki 6 Matysik 7 Tarasiewicz 8 Urban 9 Karaś 10 Majewski 11 Smolarek 12 Kazimierski 13 Komornicki 14 Kubicki 15 Buncol 16 Pałasz 17 Zgutczyński 18 Pawlak 19 Wandzik 20 Boniek (c) 21 Dziekanowski 22 Furtok Coach: Piechniczek                    v t e   Polish Footballer of the Year       Sport    1967: Lubański 1968: not held 1969: not held 1970: Lubański 1971: not held 1972: not held 1973: Deyna 1974: Lato         Piłka Nożna    1973: Deyna 1974: Deyna 1975: Maszczyk 1976: Kasperczak 1977: Lato 1978: Boniek 1979: Rudy 1980: not held 1981: Lato 1982: Boniek 1983: Młynarczyk 1984: W. Smolarek 1985: Dziekanowski 1986: W. Smolarek 1987: Iwan 1988: Warzycha 1989: Tarasiewicz 1990: Ziober 1991: Czachowski 1992: Kowalczyk 1993: Leśniak 1994: Kosecki 1995: Pisz 1996: Nowak 1997: Majak 1998: Trzeciak 1999: Zieliński 2000: Dudek 2001: Olisadebe 2002: Żurawski 2003: Krzynówek 2004: Krzynówek 2005: E. Smolarek 2006: E. Smolarek 2007: E. Smolarek 2008: Błaszczykowski 2009: M. Lewandowski 2010: Błaszczykowski 2011: R. Lewandowski 2012: R. Lewandowski 2013: R. Lewandowski 2014: R. Lewandowski 2015: R. Lewandowski                Ryszard Tarasiewicz managerial positions                 v t e   Ekstraklasa managers          Berg Dankowski Fornalik García Kiereś Mos